SUBATOMIK MANIFESTO
We are done with the glass prison.
For too long, personal computing has been hijacked by corporations that sell you magic and then install the bars. They promised wonder and delivered surveillance. They gave us beauty and took our attention. They turned the most powerful tool ever created into a slot machine for our souls.
We remember what it was supposed to feel like.
The early dream of personal computing wasn’t about infinite feeds and addictive loops. It was about amplifying human imagination. It was about tools that felt like extensions of your mind — not cages for it. It was about wonder.
Subatomik exists to bring that magic back.
But we’re not going back.
We’re not nostalgic for beige boxes and command lines. We’re building something new — a punk Disney/Apple for the weird, the feral, the ones who still believe technology should serve the human spirit, not harvest it.
Our Principles
1. Magic Over Manipulation
We create interfaces that feel like games, altars, and adventures — not obligations. Joy is not a bug. It’s the point.
2. Privacy as Default
No spying. No data harvesting. No Epstein-grade surveillance capitalism. Your thoughts are yours. Your context is sacred.
3. Slow Tech, Premium Wonder
We reject the cult of speed and planned obsolescence. Our tools are built to last, to be repaired, to be loved. Beauty and intentionality over quarterly earnings.
4. Physical Over Infinite
We bring the body back into computing. Physical switches. Tangible boxes. Intentional context switching. No more alt-tabbing through hell.
5. Open Source or Nothing
We don’t lock you in. We hand you the keys. Fork it. Break it. Improve it. This is your machine.
6. For the Weirdos
We don’t build for the masses. We build for the psychonauts, the cypherpunks, the book hoarders, the late-night thinkers, and the ones who still feel the old magic when they open a new device.
The Promise
Subatomik will never ask you to trade your attention for convenience.
We will never turn your curiosity into a product.
We will never build cages and call them gardens.
Instead, we offer beautiful, open, intentional tools for those who still believe personal computing can be an act of rebellion and wonder.
This is not nostalgia.
This is not minimalism for minimalism’s sake.





